              "textContents": [
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 1,
                  "paragraphTitle": "Phrasal verbs",
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [
                    "Read the rules about phrasal verbs. Then complete the examples with phrasal verbs"
                  ],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "Phrasal verbs are usually made of two parts: a verb (e.g. work, try) and a particle (e.g. out, up)."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 2,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "Sometimes it’s possible to guess the meaning from the two words, but usually you just need to learn the meaning of the whole phrasal verb:",
                    "You can’t just turn up at their house! Always call first to check it’s OK."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 3,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "Some phrasal verbs can have an object. When the object is short (e.g. a pronoun or one or two words), it usually comes in the middle:",
                    "I have lots of ideas and I like to try them out while I’m cooking."
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "paragraphOrdinal": 4,
                  "paragraphTitle": null,
                  "paragraphSubtitles": [],
                  "paragraphContents": [
                    "But when the object is a longer phrase, it usually comes at the end:",
                    "I like to try out lots of new ideas while I'm cooking."
                  ]
                }
              ],
